  "text": "In this section, we prove Lemma 1, first, for the two-hop scenario, then we extend the proof to the L-hop case. We use [9, Thm. 2] which, for a G/G/1/1 system, requires interarrival times to have DMRL property and service times to have NBUE property. Note that the updates that depart the service at the first hop, S 1 are considered to be the arrivals at the second hop, R 2 . Then, between a transmitter and a receiver at the second hop, we have interarrivals R 2 = M1 i=1 (X k1:n ) i and service timesX k2:n . In order to employ [9, Thm. 2], we need to show that R 2 has DMRL property andX k2:n has NBUE property. It is sufficient to show that both R 2 andX k2:n have log-concave density, since log-concavity implies both DMRL and NBUE properties [CITATION_1] .",
